    <dashboard name='Insights of Global Poverty' type='storyboard'>
      <style>
        <style-rule element='story-point-caption'>
          <format attr='width' value='832' />
        </style-rule>
      </style>
      <size maxheight='964' maxwidth='1016' minheight='964' minwidth='1016' />
      <zones>
        <zone h='100000' id='2' type-v2='layout-basic' w='100000' x='0' y='0'>
          <zone h='98340' id='1' param='vert' removable='false' type-v2='layout-flow' w='98426' x='787' y='830'>
            <zone fixed-size='160' h='16598' id='4' is-fixed='true' paired-zone-id='5' removable='false' type-v2='flipboard-nav' w='98426' x='787' y='830' />
            <zone h='81742' id='5' paired-zone-id='4' removable='false' type-v2='flipboard' w='98426' x='787' y='17428'>
              <flipboard active-id='1' nav-type='caption' show-nav-arrows='true'>
                <story-points>
                  <story-point caption='Sub-Saharan Africa, the Middle East, and South Asia show the highest poverty rates (~110%), driven by severe poverty, while Europe, East Asia, and North America have minimal poverty (&lt;5%). This reveals a stark global divide where extreme poverty remains concentrated in developing regions.' captured-sheet='Poverty by Region' id='1' />
                  <story-point caption='The scatter plot shows an inverse relationship between GDP per capita and poverty: regions with higher GDP per capita of 1700 have the highest total poverty rates of 118K, while lower GDP regions cluster near zero poverty. This discrete pattern suggests that  axis may represent aggregated counts represents that high-GDP regions contain more populous countries with larger absolute poor populations.' captured-sheet='GDP VS POVERTY' id='2' />
                  <story-point caption='This map visualizes Access Index scores by country, with values ranging from 6,893 (South Africa) to 34,024 (India). South and Southeast Asian countries (India, Bangladesh, Thailand) show the highest access indices, while Sub-Saharan African and some Middle Eastern nations display the lowest scores, indicating significant global disparities in service or resource accessibility.&#10;' captured-sheet='Access index by country' id='3' />
                  <story-point caption='Europe, North America, and Oceania lead in all three services—electricity (100%), clean water (95-100%), and internet (100%)—while Sub-Saharan Africa and the Middle East lag significantly across all metrics, with internet penetration dropping below 40%. This reveals a clear development divide: basic infrastructure access correlates strongly with regional economic advancement, with digital connectivity showing the widest disparity between high- and low-income regions.&#10;' captured-sheet='Access to service ' id='4' />
                  <story-point caption='The top chart shows inflation spiked dramatically across all income groups in 2022-2023 (peaking 10K for high-income), then sharply declined by 2024, while the bottom chart reveals life expectancy steadily rose from 15K to 35K years between 2015-2023 before dropping slightly. This suggests the 2022-2023 inflation surge temporarily impacted longevity gains, with high-income groups experiencing both the highest inflation volatility and the greatest life expectancy levels.&#10;' captured-sheet='Time trend in different income group' id='5' />
                  <story-point caption='Child mortality is overwhelmingly concentrated in low-income countries, with extreme poverty accounting for 115,438 deaths and high poverty for 89,201—while high-income nations show minimal figures (3,856 in low poverty only). This stark gradient confirms that poverty severity and income level are the primary determinants of child survival and moreover,mortality virtually eliminated in wealthier economies.&#10;' captured-sheet='Child Morality by Income Group and Poverty Severity' id='6' />
                </story-points>
              </flipboard>
            </zone>
          </zone>
          <zone-style>
            <format attr='border-color' value='#000000' />
            <format attr='border-style' value='none' />
            <format attr='border-width' value='0' />
            <format attr='margin' value='8' />
          </zone-style>
        </zone>
      </zones>
      <simple-id uuid='{746B812E-66A9-4D09-BB23-F7AD6B1C8B3B}' />
    </dashboard>
  </dashboards>
